The DIBR II method has been developed for the determination of weight coefficients of criteria (
w n
), utilising a limited set of mutual comparisons amongst neighbouring criteria [26]. To date, its application is noted in only two studies [30], [31]. Despite its nascent introduction to the literature, its potential is pronounced, largely attributed to its simplistic mathematical underpinning, delineated in subsequent steps [30], [31].

